### Description

I am trying to emulate the complex example at the very bottom of the [NgComponentOutlet](https://angular.dev/api/common/NgComponentOutlet) docs. I have found that when I use `ViewContainerRef.createEmbeddedView` to create content using an ng-template that contains control flow, the content IS projected to the screen but NOT in the correct place.

**Simple component that projects content into a gray box**
```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-container',
  styles: `:host {display: block; padding: 10px; border: 2px solid lightgray;}`,
  template: `
    <ng-content></ng-content>  
  `,
})
export class ContainerComponent {}
```

**Main component that uses component outlet**
```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  imports: [NgComponentOutlet],
  template: `
    <ng-template #contents>
      <!-- Removing the control flow makes it work -->
      @if(true) {
        Projected from an ng-template (should be inside the box)
      }
    </ng-template>
    <h1>NgComponentOutlet Control Flow Issue</h1>
    <ng-container *ngComponentOutlet="container; content: content" />
  `,
})
export class App {
  vcr = inject(ViewContainerRef);
  contentTemplate = viewChild.required<TemplateRef<unknown>>('contents');
  container = ContainerComponent;
  content!: Node[][];

  constructor() {
    effect(() => {
      this.content = [
        this.vcr.createEmbeddedView(this.contentTemplate()).rootNodes,
      ];
    });
  }
}
```



